Ford GoBike System Explanatory Data Analysis(EDA)¶

by¶

Hany Osman¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

The Dataset include the following features:

   - Duration of  Trip(seconds)
   - Start Time and Date
   - End Time and Date
   - Start Station ID
   - Start Station Name
   - Start Station Latitude
   - Start Station Longitude
   - End Station ID
   - End Station Name
   - End Station Latitude
   - End Station Longitude
   - Bike ID
   - User Type (Subscriber or Customer)
   - Member Year of Birth
   - Member Gender
   - Bike_share_for_all_trip

The raw dataset contains 183412 rows(trips,observations) and 16 columns(features). Data type in columns included 9 are numerical and 7 are object type.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The orignal dataset after appling data Wrangling contains 174952 rows(trips or observations) and 15 columns( features). Column names are (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip,trip_date, trip_month,trip_day,trip_hour, age). Data type in columns included 2 are numerical, 2 are datetime,1 is boolean, 1 is category and 9 are object type.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interst are trip duration, user_type,bake_id and member_gender. In addition to age and start station.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the following columns will support my investigstion:

duration_sec, user_type, age, member_gender, start_time,bike id, start_station_id and start_station_name.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate distributions of individual variables. If there is unusual points or outliers, i will take a deeper look to clean things up and take a look at relationships between variables.

From the above histogram the data is right shewed in the distribution and the bulk of the trip take less than 2000 seconds (33 minutes). In addition to the presence of oultiers which are greater than whisker length as seen above¶

So, I prefer log transformation.¶

In [26]:
# describe log of bins to define their value 
bin_max=np.log10(df_ford.duration_sec.describe())
In [27]:
# format the bins 
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2, bin_max.max() + 0.1, 0.1)
# define the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=[15,7])
# plot histogram with defined ticks and labels.
plt.hist(data = df_ford, x = 'duration_sec', bins =bins)
ticks = [100, 300, 600 , 1200, 2000,4000, 12000,53000]#Ticks are markers denoting data points on x-axes.
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks] #labels corresponding to tick marks
plt.xscale('log')# log -format of x axis. 
plt.xticks(ticks, labels)
plt.xlabel('Duration (sec)',fontsize=14)# x-axis label
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips', fontsize=14)# y-axis label
plt.axvline(x=2000, color = "black")
plt.title('Distribution of Bike Trips Duration (sec)',fontsize=16);# title of chart

After log tranformed, the histogram of trip duration show that most of the values are less than 2000 sec(33 min) with peak around 600 sec(10 min).

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Relation between Duration (sec) of Bike Trips and Age is an inverse relationship between both variables. As duration(sec) decreased, age increases. The most frequent bike riders have ages between 20 and 45( youth members). Youth members (between 20 and 45) achieved higher trips duration.

Male bike riders are a higher number than other and female riders. On contract, Other and females ride bikes on longer trips than male riders

Subscriber users are higher than customers in the number of trips, but customer users have a longer trip duration than Subscriber.Subscriber users(male>female>other) are greater than customers(male>female>other) in number of trips. Subscribers likely ride a bike during weekdays than weekends, and Customers are relatively constant along the week.

Subscriber use bike share system for all trip are about 9.9% from total bike rider.

The bike riding traffic is very high at 17 (5 PM) and 8 (8 AM) o'clock . Subscriber users are higher than Customer a long 24 hours. Male bike riders are a higher number than other and female riders during 24 hours. The number of bike trips during weekdays is higher than on weekends by about 40-50% for all gender but Weekends have the largest average of bike trip duration (sec) rather than weekdays. The jam hour is 7-9 AM in the morning and 16-18(4-6 PM) in the evening.
